Given you already have Redis in the stack, simplest approach: a thin feature flag abstraction backed by Redis, no new infrastructure.

```kotlin
// feature-flags/src/main/kotlin/com/helios/flags/FeatureFlag.kt
enum class FeatureFlag(val key: String, val defaultEnabled: Boolean = false) {
    NEW_PAYMENT_FLOW("new_payment_flow", false)
}
```

```kotlin
// feature-flags/src/main/kotlin/com/helios/flags/FeatureFlags.kt
class FeatureFlags(private val redis: RedisCommands<String, String>) {

    fun isEnabled(flag: FeatureFlag, accountId: String? = null): Boolean {
        // Per-account override first
        if (accountId != null) {
            redis.get("ff:${flag.key}:account:$accountId")?.let {
                return it == "1"
            }
        }
        // Global toggle
        return redis.get("ff:${flag.key}:enabled")?.let { it == "1" }
            ?: flag.defaultEnabled
    }
}
```

Usage in the payment service:

```kotlin
suspend fun processPayment(request: PaymentRequest): PaymentResult {
    return if (featureFlags.isEnabled(FeatureFlag.NEW_PAYMENT_FLOW, request.accountId)) {
        newPaymentProcessor.process(request)
    } else {
        legacyPaymentProcessor.process(request)
    }
}
```

Dark-launch rollout via Redis CLI (or a simple admin endpoint):

```fish
# Enable for a single test account
redis-cli SET ff:new_payment_flow:account:acct_123 1

# Global rollout
redis-cli SET ff:new_payment_flow:enabled 1

# Kill switch — instant
redis-cli DEL ff:new_payment_flow:enabled
```

**Why this over LaunchDarkly/Unleash:**
- Zero new infra — Redis is already there
- Kill switch is a single `DEL` command
- Per-account targeting covers dark-launch needs
- If you outgrow it post-Series C, swap the `FeatureFlags` implementation behind the same interface

If you need percentage-based rollout later, add a `rolloutPercent` check using a hash of `accountId` — ~10 lines. But for dark-launching to specific accounts, this is enough.
